<div id="review_4398055559" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4398055559" />
    <a title="sologdin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin"><img alt="sologdin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1307928658p2/5610133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4398055559?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="sologdin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="sologdin" href="/user/show/5610133-sologdin">sologdin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/19637099-the-nonexistent-knight">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5610133-sologdin?shelf=of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas">of-best-sentence-and-moost-solaas</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4398055559" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9080753300345297207">Concerning a knight who is just a suit of armor but inhabited by &quot;the warmth of one who knows rules and regulations by heart and enjoys showing his own competence, and confusing other’s ignorance.&quot; Perhaps late to the game of critiquing knight errantry and feudalism, nevertheless the notion that rules and regulations may be alien to aristocracy is worthy of consideration. Definitely the text is interested in the coming into being of specific social formations: <blockquote>WORLD conditions were still confuse</blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText9080753300345297207" style="display:none">Concerning a knight who is just a suit of armor but inhabited by "the warmth of one who knows rules and regulations by heart and enjoys showing his own competence, and confusing other’s ignorance." Perhaps late to the game of critiquing knight errantry and feudalism, nevertheless the notion that rules and regulations may be alien to aristocracy is worthy of consideration. Definitely the text is interested in the coming into being of specific social formations: <blockquote>WORLD conditions were still confused in the era when this took place. It was not rare then to find names and thoughts and forms and institutions that corresponded to nothing in existence. But at the same time the world was polluted with objects and capacities and persons who lacked any name or distinguishing mark. It was a period when the will and determination to exist, to leave a trace, to rub up against all that existed, was not wholly used since there were many who did nothing about it—from poverty or ignorance or simply from finding things bearable as they were—and so a certain amount was lost into the void.</blockquote> The political question is also acute: "Absolute power often slackens all controls, generates arbitrary actions, even in the most temperate of sovereigns." That this critique distributes down from Charlemagne through the local sovereignties of subinfeudated manorialism should not be overlooked.<br /><br />Overall perhaps a bit truncated and chaotic, lacking in discipline at times, but aware of its meandering narration, form following content.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9080753300345297207" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


