  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3405200443" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3405200443" />
    <a title="Uhtred" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/109743598-uhtred"><img alt="Uhtred" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581262401p2/109743598.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3405200443?book_show_action=true">Jun 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Uhtred" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Uhtred" href="/user/show/109743598-uhtred">Uhtred</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3405200443" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8286404534509582944">What a worthy conclusion! The Nonexistent Knight is the third book of the trilogy of Our ancestors, after the Cloven Viscount and the Baron on the trees, which I have reread all together after more than 20 years.<br/>The plot is set at the time of the Crusades and winds around two characters: Agilulf, a knight made of an empty armor, all conscience and willpower, and Gurdulù, with a material body but devoid of conscience, which will become in the development of the history, the squire of Agilulf. Aro</span>
  <span id="freeText8286404534509582944" style="display:none">What a worthy conclusion! The Nonexistent Knight is the third book of the trilogy of Our ancestors, after the Cloven Viscount and the Baron on the trees, which I have reread all together after more than 20 years.<br />The plot is set at the time of the Crusades and winds around two characters: Agilulf, a knight made of an empty armor, all conscience and willpower, and Gurdulù, with a material body but devoid of conscience, which will become in the development of the history, the squire of Agilulf. Around these two characters, one without physical body and the other without conscience, orbit the other characters, among which stands out Rambaldo, who is almost another protagonist. At the beginning of the book we find Agilulf at the court of Charlemagne in Paris, where he is not at all likeable to the other knights, since he is too perfect and inflexible. And we find also Rambaldo, who is trying to take revenge on the pagan Isoarre, who killed his father. He succeeds, but falls into an ambush and is saved by a mysterious knight, who later turns out to be the beautiful Bradamante, whom he obviously falls in love with; but unfortunately Bradamante is in love with Agilulfo, and therefore refuses the advances of Rambaldo. And so far the story still seems almost normal. The story rears up when Torrismondo, a boy of about fifteen years old, reveals that he is the son of Sofronia, a woman who, saved about fifteen years earlier by Agilulf from the hands of some evildoers and believed to be virgin, had brought to Agilulf the title of Knight because he had defended her illibacy. Agilulf therefore feels he is a Knight for an invalid reason and goes into crisis, because a perfect man of honor like him cannot live with this shame. He then sets off in search of Sofronia to discover the truth, followed by Bradamante, who loves Agilulf, and Rambaldo, who loves Bradamante, with Torrismondo who instead takes another road, because he wants to find his father, who has joined the "Sacred Order of the Knights of the Grail ".<br />Agilulfo goes to Morocco in the footsteps of Sofronia, while Torrismondo goes to Curvaldia, where he discovers that the Knights of the Grail are not paladins at all, but they are tyrants who harass the farmers with heavy taxes. After a number of adventures, Agilulf finds Sofronia and brings her to the Franks' camp; in the meantime Torrismondo discovers that Sofronia is not his mother, but almost his half-sister, since he is the son of the Queen of Scotland and a knight of the Sacred Order, while she is the daughter of the King of Scotland and a peasant woman; whereupon the two fall in love, are married by Charlemagne and then become the sovereigns of Curvaldia.<br />These developments of the story, however, do not reach Agilulf, who, believing he has lost his honor, decides to commit suicide, gives his armor to Rambaldo and thus vanishes. But there is also time for another twist: Rambaldo, with Agilulfo's shiny armor, meets with Bradamante who, mistaking him for the Non-existent Knight, gives in to his flattery, but as soon as the misunderstanding is discovered, she decides to return to the cloistered life in the convent. In the final part of the book, Rambaldo goes to the monastery to convince Bradamante to escape with him. To narrate all this intricate story is a nun, Sister Teodora, who only in the end reveals her true identity, that is to be Bradamante. What a mess!<br />Like the other two books in the trilogy, this too can be read at the level of the basic story: fun, intriguing, full of humorous twists. But Calvino's vein is very recognizable, never without the deepest meanings: here we go in search of individuality. What is individuality? What sets us apart, of course. And for someone it is honor, for someone ethics, for someone will, for someone stubbornness, for someone war, for someone love; all concepts found in these characters, who entrust them with the proof of their existence. But Agilulf is the nonexistent knight, he does not exist, and therefore he is devoid of identity, he is almost invisible to everyone. It is empty, like its armor, and stands only for its great willpower. How many men like this do we know?</span>
  <a data-text-id="8286404534509582944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


