  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3502882387" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3502882387" />
    <a title="Indran Fernando" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30920756-indran-fernando"><img alt="Indran Fernando" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1463204281p2/30920756.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3502882387?book_show_action=true">Aug 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Indran Fernando" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Indran Fernando" href="/user/show/30920756-indran-fernando">Indran Fernando</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/19637099-the-nonexistent-knight">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3502882387&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3502882387" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15798280574638914368">I began this novella knowing only that it&apos;s about a talking, moving suit of armor and that some describe the work as &quot;allegorical.&quot; The most pleasant surprise turned out to be that, as was the case with Calvino&apos;s Baron in the Trees, the allegorical aspects are not heavy handed at all. There is room for every reader to wonder, &quot;What is the underlying message here?&quot; and arrive at a widely varying, even contradictory, conclusions.<br/><br/>There is also room for the reader to set aside that question and simp</span>
  <span id="freeText15798280574638914368" style="display:none">I began this novella knowing only that it's about a talking, moving suit of armor and that some describe the work as "allegorical." The most pleasant surprise turned out to be that, as was the case with Calvino's Baron in the Trees, the allegorical aspects are not heavy handed at all. There is room for every reader to wonder, "What is the underlying message here?" and arrive at a widely varying, even contradictory, conclusions.<br /><br />There is also room for the reader to set aside that question and simply appreciate aspects like the following:<br />-poetic descriptions spanning all five senses;<br />-the rushes of multiple emotions all at once; and<br />-the thought-provoking tangents taken by the narrator, who pauses mid-scene to muse about some tidbit of an idea.<br /><br />Here's an example of what I mean by poetic descriptions: "Amid the usual confusion of horses, the forest of lances rippled into waves like a corn field moved by the passing wind."<br /><br />Multifaceted emotional states were one of the most striking characteristics of Baron in the Trees. Here's one of the most memorable examples from The Nonexistent Knight:<br />"The emotion at seeing Isohar dead on the ground, contradictory thoughts assailing him--of triumph at being able to finally say his father's blood was avenged, of doubt whether *he* had actually killed the Argalif by fracturing his spectacles and so could consider the vendetta duly consummated, of confusion at finding himself suddenly deprived of the aim which had brought him so far--all lasted only a moment. Then he felt a wonderful sense of lightness finding himself rid of that nagging thought in the middle of battle, and able to rush about, look round, fight, as if his feet had wings."<br /><br />As for the narrator's tangential musings, I hesitate to give an example so that you can experience them for yourself. Suffice it to say that Calvino has the good taste to keep these interjections succinct, with a "distilled" quality. Unlike most writers who implement such asides, Calvino never lets them wear out their welcome or encumber the unfolding of the plot. He sprinkles throughout the narration small gems of ruminations.<br /><br />Here's other stuff that I liked:<br /><br />-The unfolding relationship between the narrator and the narration and the "narratees"<br /><br />-The idea that for all our hatred of bureaucracies, deep down we subconsciously crave the sense of order that they provide--because we are terrified by the all-consuming chaos of the universe. To use Calvino's metaphor, we spend our lives struggling to convince ourselves that we are floating in the soup, as opposed to just being an indistinguishable region of soup within its endless, uniform expanse... To achieve status of some kind (e.g., a military rank or title of nobility) creates the sense that one's life has meaning--what is that but an illusion? On what basis can we claim that we exist at all and that the titular knight does not?<br /><br />-Is the writer a participant in the world or an observer-from-afar? The narrator's ambiguous, evolving role in the narration explores the tension between living life (i.e. leaving her convent) versus staying indoors to write *about* it.<br /><br />-A hilarious, satirical depiction of war which brings to mind Monty Python and the Holy Grail, or the Princess Bride. The whimsical exploration of knighthood/chivalry may bear some similarities to Don Quixote, but I'll find out for sure in 2021.<br /><br />-Exploration of the murky relationship between the mind and the body.<br /><br />-An exploration of the concept of will power. On the one hand there is the Nonexistent Knight's absolute will power, such that his existence consists *only* of a righteous sense of duty, with no capacity for emotion, no need to eat or drink or sleep, and not even a physical body! In contrast, there is the vagabond Gurduloo, who has no will power at all, as well as young Raimbaut, who is smarter than Gurduloo but ultimately still controlled by his emotions (first, the desire to avenge his dead father, later passionate love). And yet a third case is the Knights of the Holy Grail, who cede all will and desires to the idol-like Grail, which moves them around like puppets and guides them to victory on the battlefield. Calvino doesn't just flesh out these archetypes, he collides them with each other in amusing ways.<br /><br />-A notion which appeared in the final story of Calvino's Invisible Cities: that the people who purport to be the most morally righteous might actually be just as barbaric and authoritarian as unabashed evil-doers. I think this can't hurt to keep in mind.<br /><br />-Exploration of ideas related to romance. 1) The more unattainable and disinterested someone is, the more attractive we find him/her. 2) To fall in love with someone is to invent a fictional character. 3) Romance is more narcissistic than we care to admit (this reminded me of the passage in Infinite Jest dealing with people's preference for voice calls over video so as to be able to look at themselves in the mirror).<br /><br />I'm tempted to give it 5 stars, but it didn't feel perfect. Gurdoloo's antics started to wear thin, and the part where he road a turtle across the sea tipped the scales too far in the whimsical direction. (Note: the protagonist walking from one continent to another via the bottom of the ocean was fucking hilarious though.) <br /><br />Comparing this work with other stuff that I've read by Calvino, I might say the following:<br /><br />-It's more succinct than Baron, while nevertheless bringing up a wider range of ideas, like Cosmicomics. On an emotional level, this novella didn't pull me in as much as Baron, because the characters were less developed (I suppose that's one reason why people throw around the term "allegorical"). Even though there are similar amounts of heartbreak in both works, I didn't sympathize with the characters as much in this one.<br /><br />-It may be a little bit funnier than Invisible Cities, but not quite as funny as Cosmicomics.<br /><br />Note: I listened to this as an audiobook while staring at the highway for 4 hours, which was a more passive experience compared to reading (I like to jot LMFAoOoO!!!!! all over the margins like a maniac, etc). I suspect that reading this, or even listening to it again, will lead me to bump it up to 5 stars.<br /><br />____<br /><br />2nd listening, 5/24/21:<br />On a sentence level, this short novel is uniquely satisfying and often beautiful. Never verbose or dense. As for the plot, it's exciting ("quixotic" or "picaresque" come to mind) and full of clever surprises. Calvino also manages to weave in themes related to self-knowledge, the value of moderation (too much discipline can be annoying and soulless, too much fervor and piety can be dangerous), and the nature of writing. I'd like to read some critical analyses of this novel, as I don't understand what Calvino's suggesting about modern society.<br /><br />In this second reading, George Saunder's "A Swim in the Pond in the Rain" has helped me better appreciate the novel's craft:<br />-Repetition (with subtle variations)<br />-Imbuing a character with a very particular trait, then letting that trait be put to the test<br />-Respecting the reader enough not to delay the predictable climaxes (e.g., battle against the Moors), but instead to deliver them early and then move onto "higher-order solutions"<br /><br />Other miscellaneous notes from this time around:<br /><br />The part where the Knights of the Round Table go through exercises to relinquish their will made me think of Sufism. It's interesting how Gurduloo lacks willpower, the Knights surrender willpower, Bradamante and Agilulf have extraordinary willpower, and Raimbaut is somewhere in the middle. <br /><br />The fictional characters interact with Charlemagne (a bit like Voltaire's presence in Baron in the Trees), which helps make this world feel more "real". <br /><br />Calvino is the absolute master of the final paragraph. With other authors, by the end of the story I'm tired and ready for a break, but Calvino shifts into this mode where the story offers metaphors and emotional reactions related to its own imminent conclusion. That type of signaling absolutely transfixed me in Baron, Seasons in the City, Palomar, Cloven Viscount, and this novel is no exception.<br /><br />I could almost bump this novel up to five stars, but my gut says to keep it at four.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15798280574638914368" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


