<div id="review_3461205436" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3461205436" />
    <a title="Thắng" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29658384-th-ng"><img alt="Thắng" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1436072721p2/29658384.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3461205436?book_show_action=true">Jul 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thắng" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thắng" href="/user/show/29658384-th-ng">Thắng</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title=" " href="/book/show/15961136-hi-p-s-kh-ng-hi-n-h-u">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3461205436" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17155289414786335057">3.5 star.<br/>Read this and you will understand why this book was listed in the set Our Ancestors. When I read this book, I can feel the air, the setting of the old age, how people used to think, to believe, and especially, their rotten behavior surrounding a knight that devoted his life, his being, his existence for order, honor, duty. He acted upon his codes strictly and would like everyone else to follow him exactly. That was one of the reasons why he was not loved much among the army of the King,</span>
  <span id="freeText17155289414786335057" style="display:none">3.5 star.<br />Read this and you will understand why this book was listed in the set Our Ancestors. When I read this book, I can feel the air, the setting of the old age, how people used to think, to believe, and especially, their rotten behavior surrounding a knight that devoted his life, his being, his existence for order, honor, duty. He acted upon his codes strictly and would like everyone else to follow him exactly. That was one of the reasons why he was not loved much among the army of the King, but he didn't care about, just like a truly noble knight. Even the most challenging task: to overcome the trap of women, of corruption, a trap that had caught so many other nobles, could not set his back on his journey. And he even changed the woman who set the trap (amazing, btw). :)))<br />His fate, on the other hand, I believe it to be unfair, but probably that was what had happened, not only to him but also to all of the people like him, and in general, his beliefs, his spirit. One can only hope that he went to a better place, and the inheritance of his armor was a sign that his glory would pass for the next generation and maybe developed to a new level.<br />The drama and plot twist in this book was fun too. It's not much related to the main plot, but it was good. The twist was like 3 slaps in the face of the reader, in a row, immediately, and it left you speechless. There was also a small revelation at the end of the book about why the narrator was so familiar with the lives that she was never acquainted with. And after all, living happily ever after for everyone, except, you know, our Knight.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17155289414786335057" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


