<div id="review_2530064860" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2530064860" />
    <a title="Robert" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/234027-robert"><img alt="Robert" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1519321845p2/234027.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2530064860?book_show_action=true">Sep 20, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert" href="/user/show/234027-robert">Robert</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/19637099-the-nonexistent-knight">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2530064860" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8719053226061157772">I love Italo Calvino. Before I ever read Calvino, I was a big fan of Donald Barthelme, and I mistakenly thought that Barthelme had forged a new kind of fiction, a hilarious, cutting breed of metafiction that had no precedent. Little did I know, at the time, how much Barthelme had drawn on earlier writers like Calvino. For that matter, he drew heavily on many other writers, I now know, going through the absurdists and going back through time. Even Don Quixote contains surprisingly modern-seeming </span>
  <span id="freeText8719053226061157772" style="display:none">I love Italo Calvino. Before I ever read Calvino, I was a big fan of Donald Barthelme, and I mistakenly thought that Barthelme had forged a new kind of fiction, a hilarious, cutting breed of metafiction that had no precedent. Little did I know, at the time, how much Barthelme had drawn on earlier writers like Calvino. For that matter, he drew heavily on many other writers, I now know, going through the absurdists and going back through time. Even Don Quixote contains surprisingly modern-seeming metafiction elements. But in the modern era, it is Calvino who is the true king of metafiction.<br /><br />The Nonexistent Knight is about just what it says it's about: a knight in shining armor whose armor is literally empty, because he doesn't exist. The knight is merely some kind of trick of force of will that allows armor to stand and move and speak. <br /><br />Amusingly, the nonexistent knight is a total prick, a stickler for the rules. Not having a body, he doesn't need to eat or sleep (can't do either, in fact), and so when he's not fighting or saving damsels in distress, he's performing the numerous administrative functions of nobility. In this way, Calvino manages to skewer both chivalry and bureaucratic mundanity with a single joke.<br /><br />As is typical with Calvino, the story contains many absurd elements. For all that, however, it's moving and earnest and heartfelt. It's not merely an extended joke. What is it about? Love, mostly. But also officiousness, violence, brutality, religion, belief, class, gender, and so many other things. Well worth the read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8719053226061157772" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

