    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1883085623" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1883085623" />
    <a title="Chris" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/854878-chris"><img alt="Chris" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1485122534p2/854878.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1883085623?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chris" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chris" href="/user/show/854878-chris">Chris</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1883085623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer541654506002483811">Calvino is a canny writer of fantasy. What I love is that the title tells all: this novella really is the tale of a knight who does not exist. When we first meet this knight prominent among Charlemagne&apos;s paladins, no character seems especially surprised that there is a brave and meticulous knight who emptily animates a white set of armor and a series of absurdly chivalric deeds. It&apos;s only as the picaresque comedy snowballs that Calvino&apos;s metafictions and politics come to the fore. We begin the n</span>
  <span id="freeText541654506002483811" style="display:none">Calvino is a canny writer of fantasy. What I love is that the title tells all: this novella really is the tale of a knight who does not exist. When we first meet this knight prominent among Charlemagne's paladins, no character seems especially surprised that there is a brave and meticulous knight who emptily animates a white set of armor and a series of absurdly chivalric deeds. It's only as the picaresque comedy snowballs that Calvino's metafictions and politics come to the fore. We begin the novel startled by the ways its characters remain nonplussed before the unexplained nonexistence of Agilulfo. Only toward the end of his adventures do we see how many of our assumptions about political hierarchy and practical philosophy function as beliefs in nonexistence. A lot of uncomfortable laughter in this read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="541654506002483811" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


